h3. Issue Summary
JQL search for SLAs is not working as expected when both are running() simultaneously

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a "Request type" (JSD Project> Project settings > Request types )named "Provision"
 # Create an "Issue type" (JSD project> project settings > Issue type) named "Provision"
 # Install "Automation for Jira" version 7.3.4 (https://marketplace.atlassian.com/download/apps/1215460/version/300004200)
# import the Automation rule like below:
# Create a ticket from the customer portal and create 2 issues for which the Automation rules should succeed in the Automation Audit log.

h3. Expected Results
Both the below SQL queries should return the newly created ticket
{code}
project = "ITSD project" AND "Time to first response" = withinCalendarHours()
{code}

{code}
project = "ITSD project" AND Holiday-helper = withinCalendarHours()
{code}

h3. Actual Results
When we run JQL for the below and one between the below works and return the newly created ticket and other doesn't work

{code}
project = "ITSD project" AND "Time to first response" = withinCalendarHours()
{code}

{code}
project = "ITSD project" AND Holiday-helper = withinCalendarHours()
{code}

h3. Workaround

This problem doesn't persist with Automation for Jira 7.2.8 so downgrading the Automation for Jira will help.

h3. Issue Summary

In some timezones, using Jira automation to copy date picker entries results in the date 1 day off.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Install Automation for Jira https://marketplace.atlassian.com/apps/1215460/automation-for-jira-server?tab=overview&hosting=datacenter 
 # Set system / local timezone to AEST (Australian Eastern Standard Time) | GMT + 10
 # Create a custom field - date picker. Lets call it Start Date
 # Make start date available on the project screen
 # Create an automation rule that copies the Start Date to Target Start. Target Start isn't natively modifiable so you'd need to use something similar to the .JSON below to modify the custom target start date.   
{code}
{
    "fields": {
        "customfield_10101":"{{issue.customfield_10901}}"
    }
}
{code}

See attached screen recording for reproduction steps: [^ScreenRecordingOffby1Day.mov]
h3. Expected Results

Dates are the same
h3. Actual Results

Dates are off by one day
h3. Workaround
You can use plusDays to offset the bug. Example
{code}
{
    "fields": {
        "customfield_10101":"{{issue.customfield_10901.plusDays(1)}}",
    }
}
{code}

When we use “*Send web request*” action for “*Issue Updated*” trigger, A4J is not sending any data in *changelog*.

However, when we use Jira webhook (*System > Webhooks*) and issue is updated, Jira is sending details in *changelog*.

*From Jira Webhook*
{code}
"changelog": {
    "id": "11702",
    "items": [
      {
        "field": "priority",
        "fieldtype": "jira",
        "from": "4",
        "fromString": "Low",
        "to": "2",
        "toString": "High"
      }{code}

*From A4J “Send web request”*
{code}
  "changelog": {
    "startAt": 0,
    "maxResults": 0,
    "total": 0,
    "histories": null
  },{code}

Request to include *changelog* information in the web request when webhook is sent through *Send web request* action in 'Automation for Jira'.

h3. Problem

defining a rule that selects the same "Affects Version/s" values on a multiple-choice select list executes successfully with not result.
h3. Environment

Jira core v8.17.0
 Automation for Jira 7.3.4
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 * Create a rule with the following conditions

When: Issue created
 rule is run when an issue is created. 
h4. If: Affects Version/s is not empty

  Then: Edit issue fields
 *MUltiple choice select field*!http://localhost:48170/j8170/s/omrwy8/817000/1dlckms/7.3.4/_/download/resources/com.codebarrel.addons.automation:automation-common-client-resources//images/aui-icons/add.svg|width=19,height=19!
h3. !image-2021-07-21-13-53-06-402.png|width=493,height=327!

Set the field value using a json expression, using the method asJsonObjectArray(keyName) to fit the documentation for [selecting a multiple choice |https://confluence.atlassian.com/automation/advanced-field-editing-993924663.html]field

!image-2021-07-21-13-57-26-383.png|width=394,height=135!

 
{code:java}
{
    "fields": {
        "buisness app2": {{issue.versions.name.asJsonObjectArray("value")}}
    }
}
{code}
 
h3. Expected Results

 Rule finishes successfully and the value is set

_!image-2021-07-21-13-54-38-254.png|width=593,height=137!_
h3. Actual Results

Rule finishes successfully but the value *is not set / copied* , it should show an execution error
h3. Workaround

fix the syntax :
{code:java}
{
    "fields": {
        "customfield_25050": {{issue.versions.name.asJsonObject("value").asJsonArray}}
    }
}
{code}

h3. Issue Summary
Customers try to edit the timezone of a field and set it on a data field using Additional Fields with smart values similar to the below. But the end result is not what's expected.

{code}
{
    "fields": {
        "customfield_10400": "{{now.setTimeZone("Asia/Kolkata")}}",
        "customfield_10401": "{{issue.created.setTimeZone("Asia/Kolkata")}}"
    }
}
{code}

This was only reproduced so far with the Asia/Kolkata timezone.


h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a rule for editing a Date Time field using Additional Fields;
 # Add the smart value structure as mentioned on the issue summary.

h3. Expected Results
Field gets set with the Asia/Kolkata timezone (GMT + 5.5).


h3. Actual Results
Field is getting set one hour earlier than what it is expected. 

 !image-2021-06-23-14-29-39-483.png|thumbnail! 

On the example above, it would be expected that the IST timezone field would be set as 10:30 PM, but it is being set as 9:30 PM.


h3. Workaround
 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
